The '''Grupo para el Desarrollo Integral de la Capital''' (Group for the Integral Development of Havana) is an [[urban planning]] effort in [[Havana]], [[Cuba]], established in 1987.<ref name=encaribe/> According to one scholar, it was "created to develop new ways of dealing with the problems created by three decades of neglect" of the city by the state.<ref name="Rutheiser2000">{{cite book|editor1= Gary Bridge |editor2= Sophie Watson |title=A Companion to the City|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T-0GNw8qk2AC|year=2000|publisher=Blackwell |isbn=9781782688150 |chapter=Capitalizing on Havana: The Return of the Repressed in a Late Socialist City |author= Charles Rutheiser}}</ref>

==History==
Participants have included architect [[Mario Coyula Cowley]], among others. In 1988 the group began organizing "Talleres de Transformacion Integral del Barrio" (neighborhood transformation workshops) which devised plans for local development.<ref>{{citation |author= Miren Uriarte |year=2002 |title= Cuba, Social Policy at a Crossroads: Maintaining Priorities, Transforming Practice |publisher= [[Oxfam America]] |location= Boston |url=https://www.oxfamamerica.org/static/media/files/OA-Cuba_Social_Policy_at_Crossroads-en.pdf }}</ref> The workshops involved [[:Category:Wards of Havana|local ward]] "consejos populares" (popular councils), and sometimes also advisors from Cuban government agencies or international entities.<ref>{{cite journal |title=The Promise Besieged: Participation and Autonomy in Cuba |author=Armando Chaguaceda |url=https://nacla.org/article/promise-besieged-participation-and-autonomy-cuba |date= 2011 |work=NACLA Report on the Americas |volume=44 |number=4: Cuba |publisher=[[North American Congress on Latin America]] }}</ref><ref name="Anguelovski2014">{{cite book|author=Isabelle Anguelovski|title=Neighborhood as Refuge: Community Reconstruction, Place Remaking, and Environmental Justice in the City|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6aEEAwAAQBAJ|year=2014|publisher=[[MIT Press]]|isbn=978-0-262-52569-5}}</ref>

