== 19th century == {| class="wikitable" width="100%" ! style="width:6%" | Year || style="width:10%" | Date || Event |- | 1858 || || The area was visited by [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|British]] explorer [[John Hanning Speke]], who became the first European to do so. |}
== 20th century == {| class="wikitable" width="100%" ! style="width:6%" | Year || style="width:10%" | Date || Event |- | 1903 || || Burundi came under the control of [[German Empire|Germany]].<ref name=Notholt2.26 /> |- | 1922 || 20 July || Burundi and [[Kingdom of Rwanda|Rwanda]] were joined into the [[League of Nations mandate]] of Ruanda-Urundi, governed by [[Belgium]].<ref name=Notholt2.26 /> |- | 1962 || 1 July || Burundi received independence from [[Belgium]].<ref name=Notholt2.26 /> |- | 1965 || 15 January || Prime Minister [[Pierre Ngendandumwe]] was assassinated by a [[Rwanda]]n [[Tutsi]]. |- | 1966 || 28 November || [[Michel Micombero]] became the first President of Burundi. |- | 1972 || 27 April || ''[[Burundi genocide (1972)]]'': A rebellion broke out which led to a genocide against [[Hutu]]s. |- | 1976 || 2 November || [[Jean-Baptiste Bagaza]] assumed the Presidency of Burundi in a bloodless ''coup d'état''. |- | rowspan="2" valign="top" | 1987 || 3 September || ''[[1987 Burundian coup d'état]]'': [[Jean-Baptiste Bagaza|Bagaza]] was deposed while in [[Canada]].<ref name=Lawson /> |- | 2 October || [[Pierre Buyoya]] was sworn in as President of Burundi.<ref name=Europa135 /> |- | 1992 || March || Burundi adopted a new constitution.<ref name=Kieh /> |- | rowspan="2" valign="top" | 1993 || 2 June || ''[[Burundian presidential election, 1993]]'': The [[Hutu]] [[Melchior Ndadaye]] won the election. |- | 21 October || ''[[Burundi Civil War]]'': [[Melchior Ndadaye|Ndadaye]] was assassinated by [[Tutsi]] extremists, starting another genocide against Tutsis and a civil war.<ref name=Notholt2.26 /> |- | rowspan="5" valign="top" | 1994 || 5 February || [[Cyprien Ntaryamira]] took office as President of Burundi. |- | 6 April || ''[[Assassination of Juvénal Habyarimana and Cyprien Ntaryamira]]'': [[Cyprien Ntaryamira|Ntaryamira]] and [[Rwanda]]n President [[Juvénal Habyarimana]] were shot down as their aircraft approached [[Kigali]].<ref name=Notholt2.24 /> |- | 8 April || [[Sylvestre Ntibantunganya]] was named interim President.<ref name=Europa136 /> |- | 25 April || An attempted military ''coup'' was averted.<ref name=Europa136 /> |- | 30 September || [[Sylvestre Ntibantunganya|Ntibantunganya]] was elected President by a new Convention of Government.<ref name=Europa136 /> |- | 1995 || 11 March || Mines and Energy Minister [[Ernest Kabushemeye]] was eaten by cannibals in [[Bujumbura]].<ref name=Kabushemeye /> |- | rowspan="2" valign="top" | 1996 || 21 July || [[Hutu]] rebels attacked a refugee camp in the country, killing more than three hundred people.<ref name=300Slain /> |- | 25 July || ''[[1996 Burundian coup d'état]]'': [[Pierre Buyoya|Buyoya]] returned to power.<ref name=Palmer /> |}
== 21st century == {| class="wikitable" width="100%" ! style="width:6%" | Year || style="width:10%" | Date || Event |- | 2004 || May || The [[United Nations Operation in Burundi]] was established. |- | 2005 || 19 August || ''[[Burundian presidential election, 2005]]'': Sole candidate [[Pierre Nkurunziza]] was elected President of Burundi. |- | 2007 || February || The [[United Nations]] shut down its peacekeeping operations in Burundi. |}
